  <text>
      <body>
         <p>Dear sir,</p>
         <p>I was in <persName ref="prsn:Carl03">Alfred's</persName> <placeName ref="plc:Lond01">shop</placeName> to receive the Razors and Penknives and thank you. The place I held temporarily in <placeName ref="plc:Lond02">Ship Yard</placeName> last year did not suit my health. In november I became frightfully ill and was driven to a cottage in the country. It was a question of atmosphere and lungs and in the country I soon rallied. I stick and shall stick to the cottage in future. It is at <placeName ref="plc:Enfi01">Enfield High Way</placeName>, about ten miles on the <placeName ref="tgn:7010874">Cambridge</placeName> Road. rent low, garden &amp;c, very neat.</p>
         <p>I am not[?] ready for activity of any kind, writing, lecturing or any thing. I do not mean to be idle nor to die yet ; but to follow out the character I have formed. [[2]]</p>
         <p>I have committed the last of my follies in adding a daughter to my family. I am now about to end my days in wisdom.</p>
         <p><persName ref="prsn:Shar01">Mrs. C.</persName> is in good health. She does not like the country so well as <placeName ref="tgn:7011781">London</placeName>. Her compliments to you, <persName ref="prsn:Turt03">Mrs Turton</persName> and family.</p>
         <p>I shall start another paper but think now of waiting until January, to let the scramble be over.</p>
         <p>I am quite ready for a call into the country, if I can pay <orig>expences</orig> any where. I had rather not go where I cannot pay <orig>expences</orig>.</p>
         <p><persName ref="prsn:Harr01">Joseph Harris</persName> is doing well in <placeName ref="tgn:7012026"></placeName>Newcastle. <persName ref="prsn:Carl03">Alfred</persName> is well situated at a moderate [[3]] rent for <placeName ref="plc:Lond01">Fleet Street</placeName>. We shall do business on a new tact[?], advertise much and have no credits.</p>
         <p>Many of my friends cant follow mew into a pure mythological description of Christianity. I hope you can, as I am sure it is the best point in infidelity yet reached.
            <p>What are you doing with <persName ref="prsn:Turt02">Master T. T.</persName>? Is he to be a Lawyer, Doctor or Parson?
         <p>If you come to London, you must spend a day or two with me in the country.
         <p>I have quite resolved on one thing, not to identify myself with the class of men now self styled Radicals. there is no good to be done on that ground â€”
         <p>respectfully</p>
         <p>R. Carlile</p>
